data.content:
Your assertions work but use generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3 but found 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Says "value was null" on failure |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is one case where `IsTrue` is still reasonable — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API. You could extract it to a helper if you reuse it often.
